1
00:00:08,226 --> 00:00:12,439
["IN STILLER NACHT"
BY PINK MARTINI & THE VON TRAPPS
PLAYING IN GERMAN]

2
00:02:20,985 --> 00:02:23,695
WITH LOVE... THE BOYS

3
00:02:33,580 --> 00:02:35,791
[♪]

4
00:04:20,395 --> 00:04:23,481
[DOG BARKS DISTANTLY]

5
00:04:43,376 --> 00:04:44,419
Hey.

6
00:04:46,421 --> 00:04:48,006
Everything okay?

7
00:04:48,006 --> 00:04:50,675
Can't sleep. Figured I'd get
a jump on work.

8
00:04:54,638 --> 00:04:56,598
[SIGHS]

9
00:05:02,562 --> 00:05:04,522
I was hoping
it was just me.

10
00:05:21,165 --> 00:05:23,875
He never would've been here
if I had...

11
00:05:24,793 --> 00:05:26,003
If I had just--

12
00:05:26,003 --> 00:05:27,087
Jimmy.

13
00:05:34,803 --> 00:05:36,847
The nuns back in Cicero

14
00:05:36,847 --> 00:05:40,475
would send me to hell
for saying it...

15
00:05:42,311 --> 00:05:44,395
but thank God he's dead.

16
00:05:48,942 --> 00:05:51,028
[INHALES SHARPLY]

17
00:05:58,994 --> 00:06:01,246
You want some coffee?

18
00:06:01,246 --> 00:06:02,331
Sure.

19
00:07:11,942 --> 00:07:14,152
[♪]

20
00:08:07,956 --> 00:08:10,667
[TIMER BEEPS]

21
00:08:24,931 --> 00:08:27,309
Got your six-piece bucket
right here.

22
00:08:28,726 --> 00:08:30,395
WOMAN: Thank you.
Enjoy.

23
00:08:33,315 --> 00:08:34,983
Welcome,
can I take your order?

24
00:08:34,983 --> 00:08:37,610
Sir? I would be happy
to help you.

25
00:08:43,616 --> 00:08:46,286
Good afternoon.
May I take your order?

26
00:08:46,286 --> 00:08:47,578
Yeah.

27
00:08:47,578 --> 00:08:52,583
I'd like a 12-piece bucket,
extra spicy.

28
00:08:56,463 --> 00:09:00,925
May I suggest
our signature spice curls?

29
00:09:00,925 --> 00:09:02,552
Sure.

30
00:09:02,552 --> 00:09:03,803
Give me a large
on that.

31
00:09:03,803 --> 00:09:05,514
[♪]

32
00:09:05,514 --> 00:09:09,726
Also, two Cokes
and a side of coleslaw...

33
00:09:09,726 --> 00:09:11,895
[CONTINUES
INAUDIBLY]

34
00:09:15,482 --> 00:09:17,567
[FOOD TRAY CLANGS, RATTLES]

35
00:09:21,488 --> 00:09:22,822
Sorry, Mr. Fring.

36
00:09:28,161 --> 00:09:32,374
[♪]

37
00:09:51,851 --> 00:09:55,522
We are currently in the middle
of a process called discovery.

38
00:09:55,522 --> 00:09:57,482
What is discovery,
you might ask?

39
00:09:57,482 --> 00:09:59,984
It's one of the most important
parts of any case,

40
00:09:59,984 --> 00:10:01,652
because it's when both parties

41
00:10:01,652 --> 00:10:03,530
are able to discover,
if you will,

42
00:10:03,530 --> 00:10:07,576
information that is relevant
to the claims at issue.

43
00:10:07,576 --> 00:10:10,495
Now this brings us to
another key term, "relevance."

44
00:10:10,495 --> 00:10:12,956
If a document or a piece
of evidence is relevant,

45
00:10:12,956 --> 00:10:15,500
that means it has a tendency
to prove or disprove

46
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:16,960
an element in the case.

47
00:10:16,960 --> 00:10:20,671
This whole thing
is just taking so darn long.

48
00:10:20,671 --> 00:10:23,174
Unfortunately, high-stakes
class actions like these

49
00:10:23,174 --> 00:10:24,926
often move
on a protracted timeline.

50
00:10:24,926 --> 00:10:26,511
WOMAN:
Well, okay.

51
00:10:26,511 --> 00:10:29,306
But some of us don't have
"a protracted timeline,"

52
00:10:29,306 --> 00:10:31,224
if you know what I mean.

53
00:10:31,224 --> 00:10:34,603
My son thinks
I should get my own lawyer.

54
00:10:34,603 --> 00:10:36,396
You have every right
to pursue

55
00:10:36,396 --> 00:10:38,315
independent
legal representation.

56
00:10:38,315 --> 00:10:40,108
Having said that--
Absolutely.

57
00:10:40,108 --> 00:10:43,570
Great to see the next generation
stepping up, isn't it?

58
00:10:43,570 --> 00:10:45,029
Thank you, Ms. Brill.

59
00:10:46,364 --> 00:10:47,574
Hi, everyone.

60
00:10:47,574 --> 00:10:49,326
I'm so glad to be
with you today.

61
00:10:49,326 --> 00:10:51,244
For those of you
who don't know me yet,

62
00:10:51,244 --> 00:10:53,163
I'm your lead attorney,
Howard Hamlin.

63
00:10:53,163 --> 00:10:55,123
Just call me Howard.

64
00:10:55,123 --> 00:10:58,709
And this is my co-counsel,
Cliff Main.

65
00:10:58,709 --> 00:11:00,295
Listen.

66
00:11:00,295 --> 00:11:02,713
I know you all wanna get
to the finish line.

67
00:11:02,713 --> 00:11:04,299
Boy, I sure do.

68
00:11:04,299 --> 00:11:06,134
But I'm gonna level with you.

69
00:11:06,134 --> 00:11:08,136
Truth is, we still have
a ways to go.

70
00:11:09,095 --> 00:11:10,514
Why?

71
00:11:10,514 --> 00:11:14,058
Because we want
the maximum from Sandpiper.

72
00:11:14,058 --> 00:11:17,061
We're pushing to get
an extra 30 percent

73
00:11:17,061 --> 00:11:18,647
on top of the penalty.

74
00:11:18,647 --> 00:11:21,107
Not because we're greedy, no.

75
00:11:21,107 --> 00:11:23,276
Because it's what you deserve.

76
00:11:24,611 --> 00:11:26,363
Now, to get your due,

77
00:11:26,363 --> 00:11:29,199
it may take
a little extra time.

78
00:11:29,199 --> 00:11:30,950
Is it worth it?

79
00:11:30,950 --> 00:11:32,035
I think it is.

80
00:11:33,578 --> 00:11:35,539
Because this isn't just
about money.

81
00:11:37,541 --> 00:11:38,667
It's about people.

82
00:11:40,877 --> 00:11:43,547
It's about you. Sally, right?

83
00:11:43,547 --> 00:11:44,797
[CHUCKLES]

84
00:11:44,797 --> 00:11:46,299
Right. Sally.

85
00:11:46,924 --> 00:11:48,009
And you, sir.

86
00:11:49,302 --> 00:11:51,179
We're sending a message.

87
00:11:51,179 --> 00:11:52,889
We're not gonna let
big corporations

88
00:11:52,889 --> 00:11:55,141
pick the pockets
of hardworking folks.

89
00:11:55,141 --> 00:11:56,809
I wanna live in a world

90
00:11:56,809 --> 00:11:58,769
where people
can trust each other.

91
00:12:00,104 --> 00:12:01,481
And I bet you do too.

92
00:12:03,441 --> 00:12:05,527
CLIFF: Thanks again, both of
you.
Thank you.

93
00:12:05,527 --> 00:12:06,735
Thank you for coming.

94
00:12:08,112 --> 00:12:09,239
Thank you.

95
00:12:09,239 --> 00:12:11,408
Oh, I feel better.
Thank you.

96
00:12:12,701 --> 00:12:14,160
Goodbye.
Okay.

97
00:12:14,160 --> 00:12:16,580
Bye now. You take care.
Thank you.

98
00:12:19,416 --> 00:12:22,293
Well, I think we just
put out a major fire.

99
00:12:22,293 --> 00:12:23,712
That was impressive.

100
00:12:23,712 --> 00:12:26,005
Erin, I'll see you
back at the office.
Okay.

101
00:12:26,005 --> 00:12:27,006
Bye, Howard.

102
00:12:27,006 --> 00:12:28,841
Howard, I need a minute.

103
00:12:31,052 --> 00:12:32,429
What's up?

104
00:12:32,429 --> 00:12:34,431
I threw a woman
out of my car,

105
00:12:35,557 --> 00:12:37,642
in the middle of the street?

106
00:12:37,642 --> 00:12:40,604
And I zip,
I just drive right past.

107
00:12:40,604 --> 00:12:42,480
That's what you're saying?

108
00:12:42,480 --> 00:12:43,732
I don't even--

109
00:12:45,358 --> 00:12:47,277
I don't know
how to respond to that.

110
00:12:47,277 --> 00:12:48,861
I'm not asking you to respond.

111
00:12:48,861 --> 00:12:50,905
I just need you to know
that I know.

112
00:12:50,905 --> 00:12:52,532
It wasn't me, Cliff.
Whoever you think--

113
00:12:52,532 --> 00:12:54,992
Yeah, that's the kind of thing
my son used to say.

114
00:12:54,992 --> 00:12:57,161
It was your Jaguar,
your "Namaste" plate.

115
00:12:57,161 --> 00:12:58,996
It was you.

116
00:12:58,996 --> 00:13:01,874
Howard, there's no harm
in asking for help.

117
00:13:01,874 --> 00:13:04,586
You got a lot of people
in your corner.

118
00:13:04,586 --> 00:13:06,963
So there's the baggie
at the country club.

119
00:13:06,963 --> 00:13:08,632
Yes.
After that,

120
00:13:08,632 --> 00:13:11,092
some clients, who you can't name
because of privilege,

121
00:13:11,092 --> 00:13:12,552
make insinuations.

122
00:13:12,552 --> 00:13:15,096
Then on Thursday,
you have a business meeting,

123
00:13:15,096 --> 00:13:17,682
and you witness
a Jaguar speeding past.

124
00:13:19,976 --> 00:13:21,561
Who were you meeting with?

125
00:13:21,561 --> 00:13:25,440
Not sure why that's germane,
but Kim Wexler.

126
00:13:25,440 --> 00:13:27,358
She came to me
for career advice.

127
00:13:32,781 --> 00:13:33,864
All right.

128
00:13:38,035 --> 00:13:39,078
Okay.

129
00:13:40,829 --> 00:13:41,872
Of course.

130
00:13:42,540 --> 00:13:43,625
Of course.

131
00:13:47,712 --> 00:13:50,507
Cliff, I know
this wasn't easy for you.

132
00:13:50,507 --> 00:13:52,467
You came to me as a friend.

133
00:13:52,467 --> 00:13:53,760
I appreciate it.

134
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:56,262
You can start today, Howard.
Oh, I will.

135
00:13:56,262 --> 00:14:00,057
Because you're right,
I do have a problem.

136
00:14:00,057 --> 00:14:02,059
Just not
the problem you think.

137
00:14:02,059 --> 00:14:03,728
I have
a Jimmy McGill problem.

138
00:14:03,728 --> 00:14:05,814
Jimmy McGill? Howard!
Excuse me.

139
00:14:05,814 --> 00:14:06,897
Julie.

140
00:14:06,897 --> 00:14:08,692
[JAGUAR CHIRPS]
Cancel my week.

141
00:14:09,776 --> 00:14:11,944
Yes. My whole week.

142
00:14:13,404 --> 00:14:14,947
Howard!
[CAR MOTOR STARTING]

143
00:14:32,256 --> 00:14:35,426
[POP SONG PLAYING INDISTINCTLY
ON CAR RADIO]

144
00:14:39,723 --> 00:14:41,432
[RADIO SHUTS OFF]

145
00:14:57,281 --> 00:14:59,659
[CAR REVS, TIRES SCREECH]

146
00:15:20,722 --> 00:15:21,930
[SCOFFS]

147
00:15:29,564 --> 00:15:31,107
Whoa, hold up.

148
00:15:31,107 --> 00:15:33,735
Justice will be served
in four and a half minutes,

149
00:15:33,735 --> 00:15:35,194
9 a.m. sharp.

150
00:15:35,194 --> 00:15:36,696
I look forward
to sitting down

151
00:15:36,696 --> 00:15:38,406
with each and every
one of you.

152
00:15:41,158 --> 00:15:43,994
Morning rush.
So, that's your station.

153
00:15:43,994 --> 00:15:45,996
Temporarily. Of course.

154
00:15:45,996 --> 00:15:49,292
But check it out:
center stage.

155
00:15:50,251 --> 00:15:51,335
What?

156
00:15:54,088 --> 00:15:56,716
That? It's garbagio,

157
00:15:56,716 --> 00:15:58,468
on its way
to the dumpster, heh.

158
00:16:00,261 --> 00:16:03,848
I know that this place
needs a little TLC.

159
00:16:03,848 --> 00:16:05,892
But this is just day one.

160
00:16:05,892 --> 00:16:08,060
Two weeks from now,
you won't recognize it.

161
00:16:08,060 --> 00:16:09,646
Where's Ms. Wexler?

162
00:16:11,021 --> 00:16:12,523
You mean, my wife?

163
00:16:12,523 --> 00:16:15,568
That's right.
Made an honest woman out of her.

164
00:16:15,568 --> 00:16:18,195
She's blazing her own trail
and I couldn't be prouder.

165
00:16:18,195 --> 00:16:20,281
So it's just...?

166
00:16:20,281 --> 00:16:22,366
Me. Just me. For now.

167
00:16:22,366 --> 00:16:24,076
But think of it this way:

168
00:16:24,828 --> 00:16:26,370
half the work.

169
00:16:26,370 --> 00:16:31,334
[SIGHS]
What happened to
the old folks? Elder law?

170
00:16:31,334 --> 00:16:36,422
Uh, I expanded the mission, uh,
to be more inclusive.

171
00:16:36,422 --> 00:16:38,382
Here at Saul Goodman
and Associates,

172
00:16:38,382 --> 00:16:42,219
we welcome all ages,
all creeds, all stripes.

173
00:16:42,219 --> 00:16:44,931
And who is
this Saul Goodman?

174
00:16:46,056 --> 00:16:48,225
You?
You got it!

175
00:16:48,225 --> 00:16:50,353
What Colonel Sanders is
to chicken,

176
00:16:50,353 --> 00:16:53,105
Saul Goodman is to the law.

177
00:16:53,105 --> 00:16:54,858
Why me?
Because I trust you.

178
00:16:54,858 --> 00:16:56,400
And...

179
00:16:56,400 --> 00:16:59,612
what happened last time,
I-I wanna make it up to you.

180
00:16:59,612 --> 00:17:02,866
I will explain at the end
of the day. Please...

181
00:17:02,866 --> 00:17:04,241
You're--

182
00:17:04,241 --> 00:17:06,452
You're just desperate
and need a warm body.

183
00:17:06,452 --> 00:17:07,620
Good luck.

184
00:17:07,620 --> 00:17:09,998
Where are you going?
Back to the MVD.

185
00:17:09,998 --> 00:17:12,040
I took half a personal day
for this.

186
00:17:12,040 --> 00:17:14,377
What if I double your salary?

187
00:17:14,377 --> 00:17:16,044
My salary at the MVD

188
00:17:16,044 --> 00:17:18,130
or what you were paying me
before?

189
00:17:19,507 --> 00:17:20,633
Whatever's less.

190
00:17:20,633 --> 00:17:22,176
[SCOFFS]
No, whatever's more!

191
00:17:22,176 --> 00:17:24,929
"More" is the word
I'm looking for.

192
00:17:24,929 --> 00:17:26,014
Did I mention...

193
00:17:27,807 --> 00:17:29,726
[EXHALES]
...the signing bonus?

194
00:17:37,025 --> 00:17:38,985
I get a say
in the decorating.

195
00:17:40,570 --> 00:17:42,363
Open for business!

196
00:17:42,363 --> 00:17:45,073
One at a time. Thank you.
I'll be right out.

197
00:18:01,257 --> 00:18:03,133
Viola, hey, over here.

198
00:18:07,304 --> 00:18:09,682
Thanks for meeting me.
VIOLA: Of course.

199
00:18:11,893 --> 00:18:13,436
I wanted to apologize.

200
00:18:15,730 --> 00:18:19,609
Leaving Schweikart, I'm sure
it looked sudden, but...

201
00:18:20,777 --> 00:18:22,737
Sorry I left you in the lurch.

202
00:18:23,988 --> 00:18:27,366
You probably had
to clean up Mesa Verde,

203
00:18:27,366 --> 00:18:29,827
everything
that happened there.

204
00:18:29,827 --> 00:18:30,912
Kevin.

205
00:18:31,955 --> 00:18:33,039
Kevin.

206
00:18:34,707 --> 00:18:37,460
Anyway, I'm sure
it's a lot.

207
00:18:37,460 --> 00:18:39,921
Actually, Mesa Verde
calmed down.

208
00:18:39,921 --> 00:18:41,965
Rich moved me over
to Sandpiper.

209
00:18:41,965 --> 00:18:45,927
Mm. Right.
I think I heard that.

210
00:18:46,719 --> 00:18:47,845
How's it going?

211
00:18:47,845 --> 00:18:50,222
It's pretty interesting
so far.

212
00:18:50,222 --> 00:18:52,767
It's a deep dive
into class action.

213
00:18:52,767 --> 00:18:54,936
We have our first
mediation session

214
00:18:54,936 --> 00:18:56,395
in a couple of weeks.

215
00:18:56,395 --> 00:18:58,606
Oh, already.
Who'd you get?

216
00:18:58,606 --> 00:19:00,274
Hope it's not
Roger Patch.

217
00:19:00,274 --> 00:19:02,234
Oh, God. Patch?

218
00:19:02,234 --> 00:19:04,070
With the vegan patties?

219
00:19:04,988 --> 00:19:06,363
What is in
those things?

220
00:19:06,363 --> 00:19:09,325
It's gotta be
80 percent garlic.

221
00:19:09,325 --> 00:19:10,326
So healthy!

222
00:19:10,326 --> 00:19:11,786
[BOTH LAUGH]

223
00:19:13,245 --> 00:19:16,666
No, it's not--
It's a new guy.

224
00:19:16,666 --> 00:19:17,834
A retired judge,

225
00:19:17,834 --> 00:19:21,004
who lives up in Santa Fe.
Casimiro.

226
00:19:22,296 --> 00:19:24,715
He seems fine. Smells fine.

227
00:19:24,715 --> 00:19:26,968
[CHUCKLES]
Well, then,
you dodged a bullet.

228
00:19:28,385 --> 00:19:30,471
I'm glad you called.

229
00:19:30,471 --> 00:19:31,889
I've been wanting to tell you.

230
00:19:31,889 --> 00:19:35,810
Everyone was so shocked
when you walked away.

231
00:19:35,810 --> 00:19:37,603
I mean...

232
00:19:37,603 --> 00:19:38,771
you were a partner.

233
00:19:38,771 --> 00:19:42,150
I'm sure it seemed very...
weird.

234
00:19:42,150 --> 00:19:44,110
It did at first.
But I get it now.

235
00:19:44,110 --> 00:19:46,403
What you're doing
to help the little guy...

236
00:19:47,530 --> 00:19:49,448
it's incredible.

237
00:19:49,448 --> 00:19:51,325
I'm just getting started.

238
00:19:51,325 --> 00:19:54,411
I really admire you, Kim.

239
00:19:54,411 --> 00:19:56,664
Changing direction
like that.

240
00:19:56,664 --> 00:20:00,292
Sometimes I question
all of it, but...

241
00:20:02,837 --> 00:20:04,964
You make me feel better
about the law.

242
00:20:07,008 --> 00:20:08,509
[CHUCKLES]

243
00:20:19,020 --> 00:20:20,521
JIMMY:
Hit and run, 15 minutes.

244
00:20:20,521 --> 00:20:24,316
Shoplifting?
I can knock that out in 10.

245
00:20:24,316 --> 00:20:25,317
Yeah, 10.

246
00:20:25,317 --> 00:20:26,443
Hey...

247
00:20:26,443 --> 00:20:28,278
This ain't fine dining,
okay?

248
00:20:28,278 --> 00:20:30,823
Our business model
is turning tables.

249
00:20:30,823 --> 00:20:32,950
So Francesca, I'm here.

250
00:20:32,950 --> 00:20:35,369
Remind me again
why I'm making a house call?

251
00:20:36,829 --> 00:20:39,082
Sounds like money.
Okay. Great.

252
00:20:39,082 --> 00:20:41,250
Great work.
[BLUETOOTH BEEPS OFF]

253
00:20:43,460 --> 00:20:44,712
Mr. Ward?

254
00:20:49,050 --> 00:20:50,134
Hi.

255
00:20:56,306 --> 00:20:57,934
[CLEARS THROAT]

256
00:20:57,934 --> 00:20:59,143
I'm an attorney.

257
00:20:59,143 --> 00:21:01,520
I have an appointment
with Mr. Ward.

258
00:21:05,108 --> 00:21:07,193
So, are you Mr. Ward--?
Okay.

259
00:21:07,193 --> 00:21:10,404
Well, good evening to you,
whatever your name is...

260
00:21:26,587 --> 00:21:27,671
[SCOFFS]

261
00:21:29,757 --> 00:21:30,841
Hello, Jimmy.

262
00:21:32,426 --> 00:21:35,054
Mr. Ward, I presume.

263
00:21:36,555 --> 00:21:38,432
As in...

264
00:21:38,432 --> 00:21:40,143
H.O. Ward.

265
00:21:40,143 --> 00:21:43,271
That is really cute,
Howard.

266
00:21:43,271 --> 00:21:44,981
So, wait, that means...

267
00:21:44,981 --> 00:21:47,900
you're the guy
who "shanked some dude

268
00:21:47,900 --> 00:21:50,402
in a rumble
near Central Penn"?

269
00:21:51,487 --> 00:21:52,947
That's very street of you.

270
00:21:53,823 --> 00:21:55,074
I thought it sounded like

271
00:21:55,074 --> 00:21:56,742
a Saul Goodman
kind of case.

272
00:21:58,786 --> 00:22:01,038
All right, so,
what are we doing here?

273
00:22:01,038 --> 00:22:02,539
I'm tired, Jimmy.

274
00:22:02,539 --> 00:22:04,959
You and me. Us.

275
00:22:04,959 --> 00:22:06,418
I'm tired of this.

276
00:22:06,418 --> 00:22:09,630
Aren't you? It's exhausting.

277
00:22:09,630 --> 00:22:11,465
Let's punch
it out.

278
00:22:11,465 --> 00:22:13,425
Are you kidding?
Dead serious.

279
00:22:14,635 --> 00:22:16,512
Hoping you get it
out of your system.

280
00:22:16,512 --> 00:22:18,555
Do I think it will work?
I don't know.

281
00:22:18,555 --> 00:22:20,099
Call it a Hail Mary.

282
00:22:20,099 --> 00:22:22,059
I have the gear.
I rented the ring.

283
00:22:22,059 --> 00:22:23,853
It's just you and me.

284
00:22:23,853 --> 00:22:25,604
And Macky, to ref.

285
00:22:28,024 --> 00:22:30,609
I'm sorry,
but have you lost your mind?

286
00:22:30,609 --> 00:22:33,737
Actually, I'm as clearheaded
as I've ever been in my life.

287
00:22:35,072 --> 00:22:37,033
You didn't even try
to hide your tracks.

288
00:22:37,033 --> 00:22:39,367
The baggie of drugs
at the country club.

289
00:22:39,367 --> 00:22:41,245
The clients you sent
to discredit me.

290
00:22:41,245 --> 00:22:42,412
Another prostitute--

291
00:22:42,412 --> 00:22:44,414
Okay, once again, as usual--
Please.

292
00:22:44,414 --> 00:22:46,125
I could go on.

293
00:22:46,125 --> 00:22:48,127
All roads
lead back to you.

294
00:22:48,127 --> 00:22:50,296
It's Psych 101.

295
00:22:50,296 --> 00:22:52,256
You want to get caught.
So what?

296
00:22:52,256 --> 00:22:55,301
Is this--? It's, like,
pistols at dawn?

297
00:22:55,301 --> 00:22:57,678
I'm trying to give you
what you want.

298
00:22:57,678 --> 00:23:00,430
What I want? I don't...

299
00:23:00,430 --> 00:23:02,141
I think
this is what you want.

300
00:23:02,141 --> 00:23:05,435
You wanna beat
the shit out of me? Legally?

301
00:23:05,435 --> 00:23:07,395
I think you can hold up
your end.

302
00:23:07,395 --> 00:23:09,606
You must have gotten into
a few good scrapes

303
00:23:09,606 --> 00:23:10,858
in the old neighborhood.

304
00:23:11,441 --> 00:23:12,442
Yeah, right,

305
00:23:12,442 --> 00:23:14,028
I could've been
a contender.

306
00:23:14,028 --> 00:23:15,112
Indulge me.

307
00:23:16,613 --> 00:23:18,032
Let's see what we see.

308
00:23:21,369 --> 00:23:23,829
[CHUCKLES]
Thanks for the laughs...

309
00:23:24,788 --> 00:23:25,915
Mr. Ward.

310
00:23:27,750 --> 00:23:29,085
[CHUCKLES]

311
00:23:37,343 --> 00:23:39,303
[♪]

312
00:23:42,139 --> 00:23:44,641
Come on. Come on,
let's go. Come on.

313
00:23:46,894 --> 00:23:48,645
I need you
to keep your mitts up,

314
00:23:48,645 --> 00:23:50,189
protect your face.

315
00:23:50,189 --> 00:23:51,774
Tap gloves.

316
00:23:51,774 --> 00:23:52,816
Come on.

317
00:23:55,611 --> 00:23:56,737
Okay,
go ahead.

318
00:24:00,408 --> 00:24:02,368
Come on, Howard.
Come on.

319
00:24:05,413 --> 00:24:08,207
Yeah! I'm the champ!

320
00:24:08,207 --> 00:24:09,708
Hey, look at me!

321
00:24:11,001 --> 00:24:11,961
Come on.

322
00:24:11,961 --> 00:24:13,670
Here we go. Here we go.

323
00:24:19,343 --> 00:24:20,428
Hit me.

324
00:24:21,137 --> 00:24:23,097
Hey, take a shot.

325
00:24:23,097 --> 00:24:24,556
Come on, take a swing.

326
00:24:24,556 --> 00:24:25,599
Oh!

327
00:24:29,103 --> 00:24:30,229
[GRUNTS]

328
00:24:30,229 --> 00:24:32,273
All right, all right,
all right.

329
00:24:33,399 --> 00:24:36,026
[GRUNTING]

330
00:24:43,117 --> 00:24:44,534
[CHUCKLES]

331
00:24:49,373 --> 00:24:51,917
[GROANS]

332
00:24:51,917 --> 00:24:52,918
Here we go.

333
00:24:52,918 --> 00:24:56,172
[GRUNTING]

334
00:24:58,966 --> 00:25:00,426
Okay. Okay.

335
00:25:10,518 --> 00:25:13,605
[GRUNTING]

336
00:25:30,456 --> 00:25:32,833
You've mistaken my kindness
for weakness.

337
00:25:32,833 --> 00:25:35,669
I'd like to think that tonight
made a difference.

338
00:25:36,795 --> 00:25:39,089
I'd like to think
that this ends it.

339
00:25:41,925 --> 00:25:43,219
Probably not.

340
00:25:53,896 --> 00:25:55,981
[GROANING]

341
00:26:13,290 --> 00:26:14,333
How'd it go?

342
00:26:16,043 --> 00:26:17,461
Pretty much
as expected.

343
00:26:18,504 --> 00:26:20,714
So we're on?
Yes.

344
00:26:22,174 --> 00:26:24,634
Anything in particular
you want me to look for?

345
00:26:24,634 --> 00:26:25,761
No.

346
00:26:27,721 --> 00:26:30,140
I need to know
everything he does

347
00:26:30,140 --> 00:26:32,226
and everyone he talks to.

348
00:26:32,226 --> 00:26:33,727
You got it.

349
00:26:33,727 --> 00:26:36,688
Okay, then.
I'll see you Friday.

350
00:27:06,843 --> 00:27:08,596
[CAR MOTOR STARTS]

351
00:27:15,185 --> 00:27:16,686
[CAR MOTOR STARTS]

352
00:28:05,735 --> 00:28:07,821
[CAR APPROACHING]

353
00:28:39,478 --> 00:28:41,355
What are you doing?

354
00:28:41,355 --> 00:28:43,607
Put the ice pack on it.

355
00:28:43,607 --> 00:28:46,610
I gotta see if this
will work. I mean...

356
00:28:46,610 --> 00:28:48,696
I got court first thing
in the morning.

357
00:28:48,696 --> 00:28:50,864
I can't show up
looking like Leon Spinks.

358
00:28:50,864 --> 00:28:51,948
Why not?

359
00:28:52,949 --> 00:28:54,993
I'd say you'd be
missing a bet.

360
00:28:54,993 --> 00:28:57,996
"I'm Saul Goodman. Pow.
I fight for you."

361
00:28:57,996 --> 00:29:00,082
[JIMMY CHUCKLES]

362
00:29:02,876 --> 00:29:04,587
How'd it go with Viola?

363
00:29:06,255 --> 00:29:11,051
I got a name.
Rand Casimiro, retired judge.

364
00:29:11,051 --> 00:29:13,637
Wow, you wormed it
out of her. Nice work.

365
00:29:13,637 --> 00:29:16,640
I don't know him,
but I found a picture

366
00:29:16,640 --> 00:29:18,100
in the <i>Bar Journal.</i>

367
00:29:27,610 --> 00:29:29,945
Ahh. Love the 'stache.

368
00:29:29,945 --> 00:29:32,489
That's a lot less face
to worry about.

369
00:29:32,489 --> 00:29:33,865
Unless he shaves.

370
00:29:33,865 --> 00:29:35,909
JIMMY:
Are you kidding?
Those handlebars?

371
00:29:35,909 --> 00:29:38,036
No, that's years of grooming.
KIM: True.

372
00:29:45,502 --> 00:29:46,962
"I'll fight for you," huh?

373
00:29:49,172 --> 00:29:50,257
Yeah.

374
00:30:07,733 --> 00:30:11,445
I should have left Howard
standing there like a yutz.

375
00:30:11,445 --> 00:30:15,073
Instead, I let him
suck me into his game.

376
00:30:16,533 --> 00:30:18,076
Why'd I do that?

377
00:30:19,745 --> 00:30:21,871
You had your reasons.

378
00:30:21,871 --> 00:30:22,956
I did?

379
00:30:23,791 --> 00:30:24,874
Like what?

380
00:30:30,673 --> 00:30:33,717
Because you know.

381
00:30:36,011 --> 00:30:37,095
I know.

382
00:30:38,347 --> 00:30:39,931
[SIGHS]

383
00:30:41,891 --> 00:30:43,893
You know what's coming next.

384
00:30:46,396 --> 00:30:49,566
[POP MUSIC PLAYING
INDISTINCTLY FROM CAR]

385
00:31:05,207 --> 00:31:07,626
<i>♪ I'm not the only one</i>
<i>That holds you ♪</i>

386
00:31:07,626 --> 00:31:09,919
<i>♪ I never ever</i>
<i>Should have told you ♪</i>

387
00:31:09,919 --> 00:31:11,879
<i>♪ You're my only... ♪</i>

388
00:31:11,879 --> 00:31:13,965
[SONG CONTINUES, INDISTINCTLY]

389
00:31:23,308 --> 00:31:24,643
[SONG ENDS]

390
00:31:37,906 --> 00:31:38,948
[GRUNTS]

391
00:31:49,626 --> 00:31:51,002
Hey, Mike.
Hey.

392
00:31:54,047 --> 00:31:55,883
You good?

393
00:31:55,883 --> 00:31:57,634
Yep. All quiet.

394
00:31:57,634 --> 00:31:59,969
You guys get dinner?

395
00:31:59,969 --> 00:32:01,137
Yeah. We ate.

396
00:32:13,942 --> 00:32:16,612
"Bike at 5:40"?

397
00:32:16,612 --> 00:32:18,363
Just a kid
dropping off menus.

398
00:32:18,363 --> 00:32:19,573
It was legit.

399
00:32:21,116 --> 00:32:22,284
MIKE:
He asleep?

400
00:32:27,623 --> 00:32:28,707
All right.

401
00:32:31,877 --> 00:32:32,961
Hey.

402
00:32:38,007 --> 00:32:41,094
[BRUSH SCRUBBING]

403
00:32:53,398 --> 00:32:55,692
MIKE:
Part of the reason
we set it up this way

404
00:32:55,692 --> 00:32:57,653
is so you can get
some rest.

405
00:32:57,653 --> 00:32:59,571
No news yet, I take it.

406
00:33:05,076 --> 00:33:06,536
It's a waiting game.

407
00:33:09,205 --> 00:33:11,541
Wherever he is now,
sooner or later,

408
00:33:11,541 --> 00:33:13,543
he's gonna end up
right here.

409
00:33:20,300 --> 00:33:23,637
He can't strike. Not yet.

410
00:33:26,181 --> 00:33:27,265
So.

411
00:33:52,332 --> 00:33:55,002
Tell your men
that we are going out.

412
00:34:57,606 --> 00:34:59,566
The other end of the tunnel
is plugged

413
00:34:59,566 --> 00:35:03,319
with 420 cubic yards of dirt.

414
00:35:03,319 --> 00:35:06,656
Topped with a cement pad,
no one's coming in that way.

415
00:35:12,037 --> 00:35:13,789
I could put more guys
on the place

416
00:35:13,789 --> 00:35:15,457
if that's what
you're thinking.

417
00:35:23,715 --> 00:35:24,967
I'll be upstairs.

418
00:35:34,183 --> 00:35:36,394
[♪]

419
00:35:54,704 --> 00:35:57,749
[LOW ELECTRICAL HUMMING]

420
00:36:38,498 --> 00:36:39,541
[CLICKS]

421
00:37:33,136 --> 00:37:35,304
[SIGHS]

422
00:38:19,682 --> 00:38:21,684
MAN 1 [READING, IN GERMAN]:
"Who scored the winning goal

423
00:38:21,684 --> 00:38:23,895
for Germany
in the 1990 World Cup Final?"

424
00:38:23,895 --> 00:38:25,981
[GAME CHIMING]

425
00:38:29,776 --> 00:38:31,486
WOMAN [IN GERMAN]:
Yes, awesome!

426
00:38:31,486 --> 00:38:32,570
Cool!

427
00:38:33,905 --> 00:38:36,324
"Who was the first
female astronaut?"

428
00:38:37,700 --> 00:38:39,911
Sally Ride,
yes?

429
00:38:39,911 --> 00:38:41,079
Is that right?

430
00:38:42,998 --> 00:38:44,332
Yes, of course.

431
00:38:44,332 --> 00:38:46,209
Valentina Tereshkova.

432
00:38:52,590 --> 00:38:53,675
Sally Ride.

433
00:38:55,302 --> 00:38:57,720
[GAME CHIMES]

434
00:38:57,720 --> 00:38:59,681
Dammit.

435
00:38:59,681 --> 00:39:01,975
BARTENDER [IN GERMAN]:
What can I get you?

436
00:39:01,975 --> 00:39:04,560
MAN 2 [IN GERMAN]:
Martini, please.

437
00:39:04,560 --> 00:39:06,104
BARTENDER:
Vodka or gin?

438
00:39:07,897 --> 00:39:09,858
MAN 2 [IN ENGLISH]:
Give me whatever you like.

439
00:39:09,858 --> 00:39:11,860
BARTENDER [IN ENGLISH]:
You're American?

440
00:39:11,860 --> 00:39:14,321
I guess you could spot us
a mile away.

441
00:39:14,321 --> 00:39:16,031
Yeah, I'm here on business.

442
00:39:16,031 --> 00:39:19,534
BARTENDER: From California?
No. New Mexico.

443
00:39:19,534 --> 00:39:22,495
It's another state.

444
00:39:22,495 --> 00:39:26,166
I mean, it's like California,
just less traffic, you know?

445
00:39:29,544 --> 00:39:30,628
Thank you.

446
00:39:31,754 --> 00:39:34,007
A little town called Jemez.

447
00:39:34,007 --> 00:39:35,050
Jemez?

448
00:39:38,053 --> 00:39:41,181
I almost visited there once.
Almost?

449
00:39:41,181 --> 00:39:43,474
Hm. This close.

450
00:39:45,268 --> 00:39:47,020
Well, I'm sorry
you didn't make it.

451
00:39:47,020 --> 00:39:49,731
It's a beautiful place.
The hot springs.

452
00:39:49,731 --> 00:39:53,609
Yes. That's what I was wanting,
you know, the, uh...

453
00:39:53,609 --> 00:39:54,903
Hm...

454
00:39:54,903 --> 00:39:56,445
[SIGHS]
How do you say?

455
00:39:57,488 --> 00:39:58,740
[SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

456
00:39:58,740 --> 00:40:00,742
The minerals?

457
00:40:00,742 --> 00:40:05,413
Oh, it's similar. Yes.
So relaxing for the muscles.

458
00:40:07,874 --> 00:40:12,670
Well, maybe you'll get
to go there another time.

459
00:40:12,670 --> 00:40:17,050
I don't think so.
But it's a nice idea.

460
00:40:20,303 --> 00:40:23,973
Maybe a trip to Karlovy Vary.
The baths there are wonderful.

461
00:40:25,225 --> 00:40:26,351
To...

462
00:40:28,519 --> 00:40:32,232
Karlovy Vary.
Vary.

463
00:40:32,232 --> 00:40:34,401
[CHUCKLES]

464
00:40:34,401 --> 00:40:36,361
Not far from Prague.

465
00:40:36,361 --> 00:40:38,947
Oh, Prague. Yes. There.

466
00:40:38,947 --> 00:40:40,907
I always wanted
to go visit there.

467
00:40:42,700 --> 00:40:43,743
I'm Ben.

468
00:40:44,744 --> 00:40:45,787
Ben.

469
00:40:47,663 --> 00:40:49,457
Hello.
I'm Margarethe.

470
00:40:50,708 --> 00:40:52,961
Oh, it's very nice
to meet you, Margarethe.

471
00:40:54,003 --> 00:40:56,047
I knew
his work was dangerous,

472
00:40:57,257 --> 00:40:59,884
but I never imagined
such a thing.

473
00:40:59,884 --> 00:41:04,180
Well,
I suppose I tried not to.

474
00:41:05,390 --> 00:41:06,599
That is terrible.

475
00:41:08,810 --> 00:41:10,979
What kind of accident was it?

476
00:41:10,979 --> 00:41:13,315
A cave-in.
A cave-in?

477
00:41:14,565 --> 00:41:16,692
He was able
to save his men,

478
00:41:16,692 --> 00:41:18,903
he got them out,
but then,

479
00:41:18,903 --> 00:41:20,822
the structure collapsed.

480
00:41:20,822 --> 00:41:22,740
So your husband
was a hero.

481
00:41:22,740 --> 00:41:24,867
[CHUCKLES]

482
00:41:24,867 --> 00:41:28,121
He would never accept that.
My Werner was too humble.

483
00:41:31,333 --> 00:41:33,042
What were they building there?

484
00:41:33,042 --> 00:41:36,087
My husband didn't talk
much about his work.

485
00:41:36,087 --> 00:41:37,880
It was very secretive.

486
00:41:39,299 --> 00:41:43,428
Well, surely he must
have told you something.

487
00:41:43,428 --> 00:41:44,971
The lawyers
came to my house,

488
00:41:44,971 --> 00:41:47,265
I asked questions,
they wouldn't say much.

489
00:41:49,809 --> 00:41:50,893
Lawyers.

490
00:41:53,188 --> 00:41:55,482
They went through
Werner's things,

491
00:41:55,482 --> 00:41:57,775
took anything
that they called...

492
00:41:58,901 --> 00:42:00,445
Oh, how do you say it?

493
00:42:02,447 --> 00:42:05,116
Proprietary? I'm sorry,
my English is--

494
00:42:05,116 --> 00:42:07,494
Oh, it's excellent.
[CHUCKLES]

495
00:42:08,786 --> 00:42:10,788
I didn't care about it.

496
00:42:10,788 --> 00:42:14,625
All the boxes of folders,
his papers.

497
00:42:14,625 --> 00:42:16,544
Why do I need
all that stuff?

498
00:42:20,089 --> 00:42:21,632
What about your husband's men?

499
00:42:23,009 --> 00:42:25,387
I mean, they must have said
something to you.

500
00:42:25,387 --> 00:42:29,765
Werner loved <i>seine Jungs,</i>
his boys.

501
00:42:31,809 --> 00:42:33,936
But I never even met them.

502
00:42:33,936 --> 00:42:36,147
What do you mean?
Not even at the funeral?

503
00:42:37,357 --> 00:42:39,901
You'd think they'd want
to pay respect

504
00:42:39,901 --> 00:42:41,861
to the man who saved
their lives.

505
00:42:41,861 --> 00:42:45,156
They sent flowers,
keepsakes, and so on,

506
00:42:45,156 --> 00:42:47,867
but not one of them
showed his face.

507
00:42:51,620 --> 00:42:55,291
Well, that is...

508
00:42:56,876 --> 00:42:59,170
[SIGHS]
It's just not right.

509
00:43:00,963 --> 00:43:02,340
Mm-hm.

510
00:43:05,843 --> 00:43:07,554
Let's speak of something else.

511
00:43:10,139 --> 00:43:11,974
Tell me about New Mexico.

512
00:43:13,142 --> 00:43:14,685
[CHUCKLES]

513
00:43:15,562 --> 00:43:16,687
You would love it.

514
00:43:17,688 --> 00:43:19,482
BEN:
So how do you say it?

515
00:43:19,482 --> 00:43:22,651
[MARGARETHE GIGGLES,
THEN SPEAKS IN GERMAN]

516
00:43:23,819 --> 00:43:25,613
[BEN REPEATS AFTER MARGARETHE]

517
00:43:25,613 --> 00:43:28,866
MARGARETHE: Not bad. Not bad.
BEN: Yeah?

518
00:43:28,866 --> 00:43:30,910
People don't live
in them anymore,

519
00:43:30,910 --> 00:43:32,495
but for centuries, they...

520
00:43:34,956 --> 00:43:38,084
Here we are.
My little cave.

521
00:43:38,084 --> 00:43:39,252
It's nice.

522
00:43:40,253 --> 00:43:41,379
So quiet.

523
00:43:41,379 --> 00:43:43,548
[MARGARETHE GIGGLES]

524
